comment.body:
When I checked the job definition on ci.jenkins.io, it showed that a cron schedule was enabled but the schedule was empty.

When I copied from cron definition from the Jenkinsfile to the job definition, it saved as expected.  The job should run daily as scheduled now.

I don't know why the Pipeline job definition did not store the cron definition in the job.  That surprised me and needs more exploration.  I'll try to duplicate that behavior on another job.

fix: Resolve cross-platform path separator issues in Infrastructure tests

Fix Windows CI failures by using Path.Combine for cross-platform compatibility:

- TemplateCopyServiceTests: Use Path.Combine for target path expectations
  to handle Windows backslash vs Unix forward slash differences
- TemplateSetDiscoveryServiceTests: Use Path.Combine for mock setups
  to ensure paths match what the service implementation generates
- Add System.IO using statements for Path class access

The infrastructure service implementations correctly use Path.Combine,
but the test mocks were expecting Unix-style paths which failed on
Windows CI where Path.Combine produces mixed separators.

Tests now pass on both Unix and Windows platforms.

issue.title: feat(ux): show selected task details in Context panel
issue.body:
This commit implements the context panel feature.

When a user selects a task in the timeline or dependency graph, its details are now displayed in the right-hand "Context" panel.

Key features:
- **Task Selection:** Clicking a task in the timeline or graph selects it. The selection can be moved with the Up/Down arrow keys when the timeline or graph view has focus.
- **Context Panel Display:** The context panel shows the selected task's name, ID, duration, dependencies, slack, CPM timings (ES, EF, LS, LF), and critical status.
- **Task Actions:** The panel includes buttons to Edit, Duplicate, Deactivate/Activate, and Delete the selected task.
- **Keyboard Navigation:** Pressing 'Enter' on a selected task moves focus to the context panel for improved accessibility.

Publish incredibly high performance websites and applications right from GitHub. The Netlify platform connects your repositories to an all-in-one workflow for global CDN deployment, continuous integration, and automatic (and free) HTTPS. ## Features

### Push your site live, directly from GitHub
Deploy your site to an ultra-redundant global CDN that’s purpose built for serving pages and assets quickly and consistently.

### Automate deployment
Netlify’s built-in Continuous Deployment automatically runs your build commands and deploys the result whenever you push to your Git repository.

### Add a custom domain
Purchase domains and manage DNS zones and records right inside of Netlify.

### HTTPS is automatic
Your site will automatically be secured with a free TLS certificate from Let’s Encrypt.

### Deploy Previews
Netlify’s Deploy Previews streamlined your workflow by giving you a unique, permanent URL to check what your changes will be like in production whenever you submit a pull request.

### And a lot more!
Netlify includes solutions for forms, identity, and even custom functions powered by AWS Lambda. And all this functionality can be configured directly in your repo.

## actions taken
- Ran an e2e-style coverage pass that exercises the Typer CLI trade entry (via Typer’s runner) while stubbing the heavy main() logic to avoid real network calls. This captures which modules the CLI path imports/executes without placing orders.
- Verified the TYPES_V2 default is ON in the feature flags.

Checkpoint

- Coverage HTML written to htmlcov; terminal summary captured module hits and coverage.

## files executed by “alchemiser trade --ignore-market-hours” path (representative non-zero hits)
Note: This run uses the CLI path (Typer) with main() stubbed to avoid live trading; it reflects modules imported/executed by the CLI command path. Many business modules are imported (hence appear), but deeper trading/execution code isn’t fully exercised without live trading.

- CLI and entry

- DI/container and flags
  - infrastructure_providers.py — 90%

  - config.py — 100%

- Typed-path data provider (default with TYPES_V2 ON)
  - typed_data_provider_adapter.py — 65%
  - alpaca_manager.py — 15%
  - market_data_client.py — 16%
  - market_data_service.py — 11%
- Trading facade (imported; not the default when TYPES_V2=1)
  - unified_data_provider_facade.py — 34% (imported by tests to assert OFF behavior)
- Higher layers (imported by CLI; mostly unexecuted logic)
  - trading_service_manager.py — 14%
  - engine_service.py — 10%
  - cli_formatter.py — 4%
  - Multiple domain models/strategies modules show low-to-moderate coverage because they’re imported on startup

If you want the exact file list strictly with executed lines from a “real” CLI invocation (not stubbed), I can run coverage on the actual command with env stubbed keys; however, it will try to hit network without additional mocking. I can also generate a JSON coverage report for machine-parsing on request.

## TYPES_V2 default (confirm)
- Default is ON. See: feature_flags.py
  - type_system_v2_enabled(default: bool = True) → returns True by default unless TYPES_V2_ENABLED is explicitly falsey.
- DI wiring: with flag ON, the container resolves the typed adapter; legacy facade only when explicitly OFF.

## adapter docstring clarity (confirm)
- typed_data_provider_adapter.py clearly states:
  - It exposes get_data/get_current_price/get_latest_quote with legacy-shaped signatures.
  - It routes to typed services (AlpacaManager/MarketDataClient).
  - It avoids instantiating the legacy UnifiedDataProviderFacade when TYPES_V2 is enabled.

## quick recommendations (minimize tech debt)
- Keep TYPES_V2 as the only runtime path; delete the legacy facade after parity tests pass for remaining slices.
- Replace legacy-shaped get_data usage in strategies with typed repositories/DTO→domain mappers; then remove the adapter.
- Enforce strict typing and DTO→domain conversion at boundaries; fail fast instead of falling back.

- Coverage on trade CLI and list files: Done (stubbed main to avoid side effects); key modules listed above.
- Make TYPES_V2 the default: Done (default True; container prefers typed adapter).
- Clarify adapter docstring: Done (explicit about purpose vs facade).
- Propose “right thing to do”: Done (typed-first, remove legacy/adapter post-migration).
- Open PR(s): Blocked without confirming remote branch state/push. I can prepare a PR description and open it once the branch is pushed, or open one against the existing ‘type-system’ branch if it’s on GitHub.
